              <blockquote>
                <p>About time</p>
                <small>an underground station where underground trains depart and leave, esp in London</small>
              </blockquote>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>
            <strong>A: </strong>Don’t you want to get a job so you can save money for yourself? <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>I know. It’s about time I’ll look for a job. <br><br>

            <em>use 'about time' in your own sentence</em><br><br>
            
            <hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>All the best</p>
                <small>You can say this to wish someone good luck when you're saying good-bye.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>
            <strong>A: </strong>Are you leaving for England early tomorrow? <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Yes, I might stay there for a year. <br>
            <strong>A: </strong>Oh I see. I wish you all the best. <br><br>


            <em>Use 'all the best' in your own sentence</em><br><br>

            <hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>All well and good</p>
                <small>You can say this about something that's good, but not exactly what's needed or not all that's needed.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>How was your presentation yesterday? <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>It’s all well and good. <br><br>

            <em>use 'all well and good' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>Allow me </p>
                <small>This is a polite thing to say when you're offering to help someone.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>This books are so heavy, I think I can’t open the door. <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>No problem, allow me. <br><br>

            <em>use 'allow me' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>


            <blockquote>
                <p>As a matter of fact</p>
                <small>You can say this when you're adding information, or when you're correcting wrong information.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>You told me about the nice places in Cebu. My friend said maybe it wasn’t true. <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>It is true! As a matter of fact, I can show you pictures and videos when I went there. <br><br>

            <em>use 'as a matter of fact' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>


            <blockquote>
                <p>As far as I know</p>
                <small>You can say this when telling someone what you know so far, when there could be other facts you don't know.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>How much is the population of Japan this year? <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>I’m not sure but as far as I know it was around 126 million plus. <br><br>

            <em>use 'as far as I know' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>As far as I’m concerned</p>
                <small>You can say this when giving your personal opinion or views about something.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>Is this place good for dinner? <br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Definitely. As far as I’m concerned, it’s the best restaurant in town. <br><br>


            <em>use 'As far as I'm concerned' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>At Least</p>
                <small>You can use this when mentioning something positive in a generally negative situation or context.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>Oh no! It’s raining outside.<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>At least we have a board game to play inside while waiting for the rain to stop.<br><br>


            <em>use 'at least' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>

            <blockquote>
                <p>At the Same Time</p>
                <small>You can use this to introduce another fact or view that should be considered alongside those already mentioned.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>I was cleaning the house because it was so messy, at the same time I was cooking dinner for my kids. <br> When they arrived, everything was clean and ready.<br><br>


            <em>use 'at least' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>            

            <blockquote>
                <p>Back in the old days</p>
                <small>You can say this if you're talking about a time long ago, or a time much earlier in your life.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>How do you think children are playing long time ago?<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Well, back in the old days, children can go outside to play.<br><br>


            <em>use ' back in the old days' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>      


            <blockquote>
                <p>Be my guest</p>
                <small>You can say this instead of "yes" if someone asks you for permission to do something.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>Can I come in?<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Sure! Be my guest.<br><br>


            <em>use 'be my guest' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>


            <blockquote>
                <p>Be right there</p>
                <small>You can use this to tell someone you'll be with them very soon.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>Hey, where are you at this moment? Everyone’s waiting.<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>I’ll be right there.<br><br>


            <em>use 'be right there' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>

            
