            <strong>A: </strong>What do we need to bring tomorrow?<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Be sure to bring your notes for the next lesson.<br><br>


            <em>use 'be sure to' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>


            <blockquote>
                <p>Believe it or not</p>
                <small>You can say this when sharing some unexpected news or surprising information.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>Believe it or not, Ayala mall is giving 80% less for all the product.<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>Really? I’d better go there tomorrow.<br><br>


            <em>use 'believe it or not' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>



            <blockquote>
                <p>Better late than never</p>
                <small>You can say this when you're glad something's happened, but you wish it'd happened sooner.</small>
            </blockquote><br>

            <strong>Conversation:</strong><br><br>

            <strong>A: </strong>So sorry for the late birthday present.<br>
            <strong>B: </strong>It’s okay, better late than never.<br><br>


            <em>use 'better late than never' in your own sentence</em><br><br><hr><br>


            <blockquote>
                <p>Better luck next time</p>
